[{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#API","page":"API Reference","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.BlackScholesProblem","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.BlackScholesProblem","text":"d ln S(t) = (r(t) - fracΘ(tS)^22)dt + σ dW_t\n\nSolves for log S(t).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.CoxIngersollRoss","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.CoxIngersollRoss","text":"dr = kappa(theta - r)dt + sigmasqrtr dW_t\n\nThe Cox-Ingersoll-Ross (CIR) model is commonly used for short-rate modeling in interest rate theory.\n\nThis type represents the exact transition law of the CIR process, and can be used to sample directly from the known non-central (\\chi^2) distribution implied by the model.\n\nFields\n\nκ: Mean-reversion speed.\nθ: Long-run mean level.\nσ: Volatility coefficient.\n\nThis exact law is used internally by CIRNoise to create a NoiseProcess with the correct distributional dynamics.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.CoxIngersollRoss-NTuple{7, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.CoxIngersollRoss","text":"Samples the CIR process exactly using the non-central chi-squared transition distribution.\n\nArguments\n\nDW: Not used but required for interface compatibility.\nW: Path history; last value is used for adjustment.\ndt: Time step size.\nu: Current value (not used in exact sampling).\np: Parameters (not used here).\nt: Current time (not used here).\nrng: Random number generator.\n\nReturns an increment from the single sample from the exact transition distribution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.CIRNoise","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.CIRNoise","text":"dr = κ(θ - r)dt + σr dW_t\n\nThe Cox-Ingersoll-Ross (CIR) model is commonly used for short-rate modeling in interest rate theory. This is a distributionally-exact process, leveraging the known χ² transition law of the process. The sampling leverages Distributions.jl. This method is way slower than the discretized version, hence it is advisable to use it only when simulation at few time-points is needed with no bias.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.CIRProblem-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.CIRProblem","text":"dr = κ(θ - r)dt + σr dW_t\n\nThe Cox-Ingersoll-Ross (CIR) model is commonly used for short-rate modeling in interest rate theory.\n\nKeyword Arguments\n\nmodifier: A function applied inside the square root in the diffusion term. It ensures rate positivity which can break due to discretization error.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.ExtendedOrnsteinUhlenbeckProblem-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ExtendedOrnsteinUhlenbeckProblem","text":"dx = a(b(t)-x)dt + σ dW_t\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.GeneralizedBlackScholesProblem-NTuple{6, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.GeneralizedBlackScholesProblem","text":"d ln S(t) = (r(t) - q(t) - fracΘ(tS)^22)dt + σ dW_t\n\nSolves for log S(t).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.GeometricBrownianMotionProblem-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.GeometricBrownianMotionProblem","text":"dx = μx dt + σx dW_t\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.HestonProblem-NTuple{7, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.HestonProblem","text":"dS = μSdt + sqrtvSdW_1\ndv = κ(Θ-v)dt + σsqrtvdW_2\ndW_1 dW_2 = ρ dt\n\nKeyword Arguments\n\nmodifier: A function applied inside the square root in the diffusion term. By default, modifier ensures numerical stability when u[2] becomes slightly negative due to discretization errors. Without this, the square root of a negative number would result in a domain error. You may override this if using an alternative regularization strategy or if you're certain u[2] will remain positive.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.MfStateProblem-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.MfStateProblem","text":"dx = σ(t)e^at dW_t\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.OrnsteinUhlenbeckProblem-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.OrnsteinUhlenbeckProblem","text":"dx = a(r-x)dt + σ dW_t\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_mean-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Black-Scholes log-price process.\n\nEln S(t) = ln S_0 + (r - fracsigma^22) t\n\nArguments\n\nr: Risk-free rate (constant)\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial log-price ln S_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected log-price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_std-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of the Black-Scholes log-price process.\n\nArguments\n\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation of log-price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_variance-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the Black-Scholes log-price process.\n\ntextVarln S(t) = sigma^2 t\n\nArguments\n\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance of log-price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_mean-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the CIR process.\n\nEr(t) = theta + (r_0 - theta) e^-kappa t\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nu0: Initial value r_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected value at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_mean-Tuple{Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_mean","text":"Stationary (long-run) mean of the CIR process.\n\nlim_t to infty Er(t) = theta\n\nArguments\n\nθ: Long-run mean level\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary mean.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_variance-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_variance","text":"Stationary (long-run) variance of the CIR process.\n\nlim_t to infty textVarr(t) = fractheta sigma^22kappa\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nσ: Volatility coefficient\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary variance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_std-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of the CIR process.\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value r_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_variance-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the CIR process.\n\ntextVarr(t) = r_0 fracsigma^2kappa (e^-kappa t - e^-2kappa t) + fractheta sigma^22kappa (1 - e^-kappa t)^2\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value r_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.gbm_mean-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.gbm_mean","text":"Analytical mean of Geometric Brownian Motion.\n\nEX(t) = x_0 e^mu t\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected value at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.gbm_std-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.gbm_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of Geometric Brownian Motion.\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.gbm_variance-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.gbm_variance","text":"Analytical variance of Geometric Brownian Motion.\n\ntextVarX(t) = x_0^2 e^2mu t (e^sigma^2 t - 1)\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.heston_mean-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.heston_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Heston model asset price.\n\nES(t) = S_0 e^mu t\n\nNote: The mean is independent of the stochastic volatility path because the volatility term has zero expected increment.\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nu0: Initial asset price S_0 (first component of initial state)\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected asset price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_mean-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Heston model variance process.\n\nThe variance process follows CIR dynamics: dv = kappa(Theta - v)dt + sigmasqrtvdW_2\n\nEv(t) = Theta + (v_0 - Theta) e^-kappa t\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nΘ: Long-run variance level\nv0: Initial variance v_0 (second component of initial state)\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_variance-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the Heston model variance process.\n\nThe variance process follows CIR dynamics.\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nΘ: Long-run variance level\nσ: Vol-of-vol coefficient\nv0: Initial variance v_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance of the variance process at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_mean-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nEX(t) = r + (x_0 - r) e^-at\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nr: Long-run mean level\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected value at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_mean-Tuple{Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_mean","text":"Stationary (long-run) mean of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nlim_t to infty EX(t) = r\n\nArguments\n\nr: Long-run mean level\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary mean.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_variance-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_variance","text":"Stationary (long-run) variance of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nlim_t to infty textVarX(t) = fracsigma^22a\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nσ: Volatility coefficient\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary variance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_std-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"diffeqfinancial/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_variance-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\ntextVarX(t) = fracsigma^22a (1 - e^-2at)\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"analytics/#Analytical-Solutions","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"Analytical Solutions","text":"DiffEqFinancial.jl provides analytical (closed-form) solutions for the mean, variance, and standard deviation of the supported financial stochastic processes. These functions provide exact results without requiring Monte Carlo simulation, offering significant performance and accuracy benefits.","category":"section"},{"location":"analytics/#Geometric-Brownian-Motion","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"Geometric Brownian Motion","text":"The GBM process: dX = mu X  dt + sigma X  dW_t","category":"section"},{"location":"analytics/#Ornstein-Uhlenbeck-Process","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"Ornstein-Uhlenbeck Process","text":"The OU process: dX = a(r - X)  dt + sigma  dW_t","category":"section"},{"location":"analytics/#Cox-Ingersoll-Ross-(CIR)-Process","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"Cox-Ingersoll-Ross (CIR) Process","text":"The CIR process: dr = kappa(theta - r)  dt + sigma sqrtr  dW_t","category":"section"},{"location":"analytics/#Black-Scholes-Log-Price","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"Black-Scholes Log-Price","text":"The log-price process: d ln S = (r - sigma^22)  dt + sigma  dW_t","category":"section"},{"location":"analytics/#Heston-Model","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"Heston Model","text":"The Heston stochastic volatility model: dS = mu S  dt + sqrtv S  dW_1, dv = kappa(Theta - v)  dt + sigma sqrtv  dW_2","category":"section"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.gbm_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.gbm_mean","text":"Analytical mean of Geometric Brownian Motion.\n\nEX(t) = x_0 e^mu t\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected value at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.gbm_variance","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.gbm_variance","text":"Analytical variance of Geometric Brownian Motion.\n\ntextVarX(t) = x_0^2 e^2mu t (e^sigma^2 t - 1)\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.gbm_std","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.gbm_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of Geometric Brownian Motion.\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nEX(t) = r + (x_0 - r) e^-at\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nr: Long-run mean level\nu0: Initial value x_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected value at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_variance","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\ntextVarX(t) = fracsigma^22a (1 - e^-2at)\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_std","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_mean","text":"Stationary (long-run) mean of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nlim_t to infty EX(t) = r\n\nArguments\n\nr: Long-run mean level\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary mean.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_variance","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.ou_stationary_variance","text":"Stationary (long-run) variance of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.\n\nlim_t to infty textVarX(t) = fracsigma^22a\n\nArguments\n\na: Mean reversion speed\nσ: Volatility coefficient\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary variance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the CIR process.\n\nEr(t) = theta + (r_0 - theta) e^-kappa t\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nu0: Initial value r_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected value at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_variance","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the CIR process.\n\ntextVarr(t) = r_0 fracsigma^2kappa (e^-kappa t - e^-2kappa t) + fractheta sigma^22kappa (1 - e^-kappa t)^2\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value r_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_std","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of the CIR process.\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial value r_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_mean","text":"Stationary (long-run) mean of the CIR process.\n\nlim_t to infty Er(t) = theta\n\nArguments\n\nθ: Long-run mean level\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary mean.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_variance","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.cir_stationary_variance","text":"Stationary (long-run) variance of the CIR process.\n\nlim_t to infty textVarr(t) = fractheta sigma^22kappa\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nθ: Long-run mean level\nσ: Volatility coefficient\n\nReturns\n\nThe stationary variance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Black-Scholes log-price process.\n\nEln S(t) = ln S_0 + (r - fracsigma^22) t\n\nArguments\n\nr: Risk-free rate (constant)\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nu0: Initial log-price ln S_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected log-price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_variance","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the Black-Scholes log-price process.\n\ntextVarln S(t) = sigma^2 t\n\nArguments\n\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance of log-price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_std","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.bs_log_std","text":"Analytical standard deviation of the Black-Scholes log-price process.\n\nArguments\n\nσ: Volatility coefficient\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe standard deviation of log-price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.heston_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.heston_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Heston model asset price.\n\nES(t) = S_0 e^mu t\n\nNote: The mean is independent of the stochastic volatility path because the volatility term has zero expected increment.\n\nArguments\n\nμ: Drift coefficient\nu0: Initial asset price S_0 (first component of initial state)\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected asset price at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_mean","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_mean","text":"Analytical mean of the Heston model variance process.\n\nThe variance process follows CIR dynamics: dv = kappa(Theta - v)dt + sigmasqrtvdW_2\n\nEv(t) = Theta + (v_0 - Theta) e^-kappa t\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nΘ: Long-run variance level\nv0: Initial variance v_0 (second component of initial state)\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe expected variance at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"analytics/#DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_variance","page":"Analytical Solutions","title":"DiffEqFinancial.heston_variance_variance","text":"Analytical variance of the Heston model variance process.\n\nThe variance process follows CIR dynamics.\n\nArguments\n\nκ: Mean reversion speed\nΘ: Long-run variance level\nσ: Vol-of-vol coefficient\nv0: Initial variance v_0\nt: Time (scalar or array)\n\nReturns\n\nThe variance of the variance process at time t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#DiffEqFinancial.jl","page":"Home","title":"DiffEqFinancial.jl","text":"This repository holds problem definitions for common financial models for use in the DifferentialEquations ecosystem. The goal is to be a feature-complete set of solvers for the types of problems found in libraries like QuantLib. For example, one can easily specify, solve, and plot the solution for a trajectory of a Heston process via the commands:\n\nprob = HestonProblem(μ,κ,Θ,σ,ρ,u₀)\nsol = solve(prob)\nplot(sol)\n\nFull documentation is in the DifferentialEquations.jl models documentation\n\nThese solvers use DifferentialEquations.jl, meaning that high-performance and high order algorithms are available.\n\nThe project is looking for contributors who would like to implement more models. If you're interested and need help getting started, talk to Chris Rackauckas in the Gitter chat.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Contributing","page":"Home","title":"Contributing","text":"Please refer to the SciML ColPrac: Contributor's Guide on Collaborative Practices for Community Packages for guidance on PRs, issues, and other matters relating to contributing to SciML.\nSee the SciML Style Guide for common coding practices and other style decisions.\nThere are a few community forums:\nThe #diffeq-bridged and #sciml-bridged channels in the Julia Slack\nThe #diffeq-bridged and #sciml-bridged channels in the Julia Zulip\nOn the Julia Discourse forums\nSee also SciML Community page","category":"section"},{"location":"#Reproducibility","page":"Home","title":"Reproducibility","text":"<details><summary>The documentation of this SciML package was built using these direct dependencies,</summary>\n\nusing Pkg # hide\nPkg.status() # hide\n\n</details>\n\n<details><summary>and using this machine and Julia version.</summary>\n\nusing InteractiveUtils # hide\nversioninfo() # hide\n\n</details>\n\n<details><summary>A more complete overview of all dependencies and their versions is also provided.</summary>\n\nusing Pkg # hide\nPkg.status(;mode = PKGMODE_MANIFEST) # hide\n\n</details>\n\nYou can also download the\n<a href=\"\n\nusing TOML\nusing Markdown\nversion = TOML.parse(read(\"../../Project.toml\",String))[\"version\"]\nname = TOML.parse(read(\"../../Project.toml\",String))[\"name\"]\nlink = \"https://github.com/SciML/\"*name*\".jl/tree/gh-pages/v\"*version*\"/assets/Manifest.toml\"\nMarkdown.parse(link)\n\n\">manifest</a> file and the\n<a href=\"\n\nusing TOML\nusing Markdown\nversion = TOML.parse(read(\"../../Project.toml\",String))[\"version\"]\nname = TOML.parse(read(\"../../Project.toml\",String))[\"name\"]\nlink = \"https://github.com/SciML/\"*name*\".jl/tree/gh-pages/v\"*version*\"/assets/Project.toml\"\nMarkdown.parse(link)\n\n\">project</a> file.","category":"section"}]
